# Native server

Ktor supports Kotlin/Native and allows you to run a server without an additional runtime or virtual machine. This page covers the limitations, dependencies, configuration, and creation of a Ktor server in a Kotlin/Native project.Here's a quick rundown of what this is about:

## Native server

Ktor supports Kotlin/Native and allows you to run a server without an additional runtime or virtual machine. Currently, running a Ktor server under Kotlin/Native has the following limitations:

- a server should be created using embeddedServer
- only the CIO engine is supported
- HTTPS without a reverse proxy is not supported
- Windows target is not supported

> ### tip
>
> Using Ktor in a Kotlin/Native project requires a new memory manager, which is enabled by default starting with Kotlin 1.7.20.

## Add dependencies

Ktor server in a Kotlin/Native project requires at least two dependencies: a ktor-server-core dependency and an engine dependency (CIO). The code snippet below shows how to add dependencies to the nativeMain source set in the build.gradle.kts file:

```
sourceSets {
    val nativeMain by getting {
        dependencies {
            implementation("io.ktor:ktor-server-core:$ktor_version")
            implementation("io.ktor:ktor-server-cio:$ktor_version")
        }
    }
}
```

To test a Native server, add the ktor-server-test-host artifact to the nativeTest source set:

```
sourceSets {
    val nativeTest by getting {
        dependencies {
            implementation(kotlin("test"))
            implementation("io.ktor:ktor-server-test-host:$ktor_version")
        }
    }
}
```


This should give you a solid starting point!

